HLO community:

The mshsl approved the starting of cross country on Aug 17 with a shortened season and limiting competitions to a dual or triangular.

Football and volleyball have been moved to a third season to happen in early spring with a shortened season 20% reduction in weeks and 30% reduction in contests.

Spring sports will be pushed back to a 4th season happening in mid may-june. Same reductions.

Other details and guidelines will come out soon from the mshsl.

post_text:
One Book | One Minnesota is a new statewide book club that will invite Minnesotans of all ages to read and come together virtually to enjoy, reflect, and discuss. Presented by the Friends of the Saint Paul Public Library in partnership with State Library Services, the program aims to bring Minnesotans together during a challenging time and to highlight the role of libraries as community connectors.

The first featured book selection is Because of Winn-Dixie by Kate DiCamillo (Candlewick Press).

Find more details on the Jackson County Library webpage: https://jclmn.org/onebook/

post_text:
National Library Week is April 19-25, 2020. To celebrate this special week we created a sensory scavenger hunt and for those wanting a challenge, the word search will offer a couple of hours of hunting, too. As we continue to be apart from our library friends/patrons, we just want to let them know that we miss them! Feel free to check out our website, jclmn.org for information about our digital collections and free resources that are available. We want to say thank you for being an integral part of all of our lives and we know that our communities will get through this time and come out stronger than ever.

Stay well, HL-O Staff, Students and Families!

Jackson County Library System
(Libraries in Jackson, Lakefield and Heron Lake)
311 Third Street, Jackson, MN 56143
Phone: 507-847-4748
Email: jacksoncolibrary@co.jackson.mn.us

post_text:
Timberwolves ‚ÄúGet Fit‚Äù Program
Students at HLO Schools

Students at the Heron Lake-Okabena Schools took part in the Timberwolves ‚ÄúGet Fit‚Äù Program throughout the month of January. Students had to track and log, on their poster sheet, all movement and activity outside of the classroom for the month to earn points. Every 15 minutes of exercise equaled one point. Students that received enough points and turned in their tracker sheets will receive a complimentary ticket to a Timberwolves game and an opportunity to shoot a free throw on the court afterwards.

Many students said they played outside in the snow, shoveled snow, played basketball, played football with friends outside, did exercises in the house, walked the dog, had dance class, and hockey practice. Wow! So many ways to keep the body and brain healthy!

Congratulations to the following students.

US National Weather Service Sioux Falls South Dakota
November 11, 2019 at 8:53 PM ¬∑

As the sky becomes mostly clear overnight, and winds gradually turn around to the south at 5 to 15 mph by Tuesday morning, temperatures and wind chills will both drop to mid winter levels. Low temperatures Tuesday morning will fall into the -5 to +5 degree range, with wind chills as cold as 15 below zero.

We hope everybody found some way to enjoy the Veteran's Day Holiday, but please don't forget to be prepared for a chilly start to the day on Tuesday! Here are some "must haves" before heading out.

post_text:
It's time for the annual Heron Lake-Okabena FFA Chapter Fruit Sales! Every single cent our member's earn through fruit sales is used for their personal use to attend conventions and conferences, fund their Supervised Agricultural Experience projects (like raising cattle, renting cropland, or starting a business), and purchase supplies or materials needed to compete at the region, state, and national level. Your support helps each member in their pursuit of premier leadership, personal growth, and career success through agriculture.

If you do not know an FFA member but would still like to order, please try our new electronic Google Form at https://forms.gle/8ypPwp76UuXteLN19 to order online!

This fundraiser ends Tuesday, October 22nd. Expected delivery date is Dec. 2nd and payment is due at time of delivery. If you have any questions, comments, or concerns, please contact Chapter Advisor Loretta Halbur at loretta.halbur@isd330.org or Chapter Treasurer Evan Madsen at evan.madsen22@student.isd330.org.

post_text:
Walk to School Day 2019 ‚Äì Wednesday, October 2, 2019

Next Wednesday is National Walk to School Day and we encourage all students to walk to school. The buses will drop elementary students off at the Heron Lake City Park and they will walk to school that morning.
Parents that drive their children to school are encouraged to drop off students at the park that morning too.

International Walk to School Day is a global event that involves communities from more than 40 countries walking and biking to school on the same day. It began in 1997 as a one-day event. Over time, this event has become part of a movement for year-round safe routes to school and a celebration ‚Äì with record breaking participation ‚Äì each October. Today, thousands of schools across America ‚Äì from all 50 states, the District of Columbia, and Puerto Rico ‚Äì participate every October.

post_text:
2019 Vision & Hearing Screenings

Our school nurse, Kathi Haberman, along with volunteers, will be conducting hearing and vision screenings for students in grades Kindergarten-Grade 5 at the Heron Lake-Okabena Elementary school on Thursday October 3rd, and in grades 7, 8, 10, and 11 at the Heron Lake - Okabena high school on Thursday, October 10th.
Elementary students who do not pass the initial screening will be re-screened on Wednesday, October 16th and High School students will be rescreened on Thursday October 24th. Should a possible problem be detected in your child's vision or hearing, you will be sent a letter requesting she/he see a physician.
If your child wears glasses or contact lenses, please make sure she/he has them along on these days.
Should you have any questions concerning the upcoming screening, please contact the elementary school at 507-793-2307 or the high school at 507-853-4507. You may also call and leave a message for the school nurse, Kathi Haberman, if you have concerns.
